{{BLP sources|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox writer | name = David Mills <!-- Commented out because image was deleted: | image = David-Mills.jpg --> | caption = | birth_place = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1959|1|24}} | occupation = Author and Politician | Political Party = [[West Virginia Democratic Party|Democratic]] }} '''David Mills''' (born January 24, 1959) is an American author. Mills has argued that science and religion cannot be successfully reconciled. He is best known for his book ''Atheist Universe'' which was published in 2004. In his book ''[[The God Delusion]]'', [[evolutionary biology|evolutionary biologist]] [[Richard Dawkins]] cites Mills' writings as "admirable work."<ref>R. Dawkins, ''The God Delusion'' (Boston: Houghton Mifflin, 2006), 44, 88–89 (hardcover).</ref> Mills claims in his books to rebut both young- and old-earth [[creation science]], as well as [[Intelligent Design]].<ref>D. Mills, ''Atheist Universe: The Thinking Person's Answer to Christian Fundamentalism'' (Berkeley, CA: Ulysses Press, 2006), 208–54.</ref>
Mills has been interviewed on multiple talk shows including [[The Infidel Guy]], [[WBAI]] in New York, on [[Air America Radio]], and elsewhere. He is also a self-proclaimed member of the [[Rational Response Squad]].{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
He currently lives in [[Huntington, West Virginia|Huntington]], [[West Virginia]], and ran for the 2016 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential nomination.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
